Problem 4

Spine Charts:

Spine Charts are similar to Bar Charts.

With a spine chart, we have a single (vertical) bar and multiple stacked, horizontal bars. To do this, change the aesthetic arguments in the aes() function in geom_bar(). , e.g.: aes(x = factor(1), fill = my_variable)

This will create a single bar on the x-axis (since factor(1) creates a one-category categorical variable of length one) and fill the bar in with colors corresponding to whatever categorical values are in my_variable.

  1. (4 points) Re-create the graph from Problem 3, but use a spine chart. That is, use a spine chart to show the distribution of Pclass. Be sure to correctly label the axes remember, their interpretation may have changed from Problem 3. Include an appropriate title (always do this).
ggplot(titanic, aes(x = Pclass)) +
    geom_bar(aes(x = factor(1), fill = Pclass), color = "black") +
    labs(title = "Counts of Each Ticket Class",
         fill = "Ticket Class",
         x = "Ticket Classes",
         y = "Total Count of Ticket Classes") +
    theme(axis.ticks.x = element_blank(),
          axis.text.x = element_blank())

  1. (3 points) In a spine chart, what are the widths of the bars proportional to (if anything)? What are the heights of the bars proportional to (if anything)? How is this different from a bar chart?

In a spine chart, all widths are the same and thus are not proportional to anything in particular. The heights of each component are proportional to the counts we observe. In a bar chart, the bars are separate and the height of each bar is the one proportional to the counts we observe.

  1. (3 points) ggplot() allows us to easily flip the orientation of our graphs without changing any of the code. To do this, you simply have to add + coord_flip() to your existing code. Do this in a separate code block for the spine chart from part (a), and discuss the differences in the two plots.
ggplot(titanic, aes(x = Pclass)) +
    geom_bar(aes(x = factor(1), fill = Pclass), color = "black") +
    labs(title = "Counts of Each Ticket Class",
         fill = "Ticket Class",
         x = "Ticket Classes",
         y = "Total Count of Each Ticket Class") +
    coord_flip() +
    theme(axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
          axis.text.y = element_blank())

  2. (BONUS: 1 point) Remove the tick on the x-axis.

Rose Diagrams:

  1. (4 points) Re-create the graph from Problem 3, but use a rose diagram. Be sure to correctly label the axes, if necessary. Include an appropriate title.
ggplot(titanic, aes(x = Pclass)) +
    geom_bar(fill = "lightblue", color = "black") +
    coord_polar() +
    labs(title = "Counts of Each Ticket Class",
         fill = "Ticket Class",
         x = "Ticket Classes",
         y = "Counts of Each Ticket Class")

  1. (3 points) In a rose diagram, what is the radius of each rose petal proportional to? What does the angle associated with each rose petal correspond to (if anything)? What is the area of each rose petal proportaional to?

The radius of each petal is proportional to the the counts of each ticket class. The angle is the same across all petals, in that it is not associated with anything in particular. The area is proportional to the square of the counts of each ticket class.

Problem 6

Pie Charts:

To create a pie chart, use a similar technique to what you used to create a spine chart in Problem 4 (hint: check the argument theta of the function coord_polar).

  1. (4 points) Re-create the graph from Problem 3, but use a pie chart. Be sure to correctly label the axes, if necessary. Include an appropriate title.
ggplot(titanic, aes(x = Pclass)) +
    geom_bar(aes(x = factor(1), fill = Pclass), color = "black", width = 1) +
    coord_polar(theta = "y") +
    labs(title = "Counts of Each Ticket Class",
         fill = "Ticket Class",
         x = "", y = "") +
    theme(axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
          axis.text.y = element_blank())

  1. (3 points) In a pie chart, what does the radius of each pie slice correspond to (if anything)? What does the angle associated with each pie slice correspond to (if anything)?

The radius does not correspond to anything. The angle corresponds to the respective counts of each ticket class as a proportion of the total count.

  1. (3 points) Summarize the differences between a rose diagram and a pie chart in no more than two sentences.

A rose diagram shows the quantities in terms of the radius while a pie chart shows the quantities in terms of the angle.

  1. (10 points) Of the four graphs we used to visualize the Pclass variable, which do you prefer? Why? Discuss the strengths (if any) and weaknesses (if any) of each.

I prefer the bar charts as it is the simplest to intepret the numerical counts and visually compare the relative counts.
The spine chart could be better for data with more dimensions as it could be combined with a bar chart, however it makes it hard to know the approximate numerical counts.
The rose petal chart makes it hard to compare relative counts for counts that are close as it is harder to see the differences in the relative radii, and similarly makes it hard to see the approximate numerical counts as we have to trace the arcs to the vertical points. The pie chart has similar problems as the rose petal chart, in that it is hard to detect close differences in the angle. We are also not able to know the approximate numerical counts.

Statistical Tests:

(5 points) What kind of statistical test could you use to show that the passengers are not equally likely to belong to any of the three classes? (think back to your earlier statistics classes)

A chi-square test of independence, where the null hypothesis is that the three classes are independent and the alternative is that the three classes are dependent.

Problem 8

(3 points each)

Facetting:

Facetting refers to the process of partitioning the original data according to some categorical variable, then creating the same graphic once for each subset. The resulting graphs are typically displayed in a grid, where each graph is a single facet of the full graphic.

This is a popular way to show how the features of the variable(s) being displayed in a particular graphic can change depending on some other variable.

With base-R graphics, facetting requires you to write a lot of code code to do the subsetting, code to display the graphics, etc. With ggplot(), facetting is very easy, as well see below.

  1. Recreate the plot from Problem 3, but this time, facet on the Embarked variable. To do this, add + facet_wrap(~ facetting_variable) to the existing line of code.
ggplot(titanic, aes(x = Pclass)) +
    facet_wrap(~ Embarked) +
    geom_bar(fill = "lightblue", color = "black") +
    labs(title = "Counts of Each Ticket Class",
         x = "Ticket Class",
         y = "Count")

  1. Adjust the ncol or nrow arguments in facet_wrap(). How do they affect the way facet_wrap() places each facet into a grid of graphs?
ggplot(titanic, aes(x = Pclass)) +
    facet_wrap(~ Embarked, ncol = 2, nrow = 2) +
    geom_bar(fill = "lightblue", color = "black") +
    labs(title = "Counts of Each Ticket Class",
         x = "Ticket Class",
         y = "Count")

Adjusting ncol and nrow sets the overall grid dimensions for the graphs.

  1. Sometimes, it improves our abiliity to compare across graphics if we have all the graphs in a single row or column, rather than having the plots displayed in multiple rows and columns. Recreate the plot from Problem 3, but this time, facet on the Parch variable using the facet_grid() function. To do this, add + facet_grid(~ facetting_variable) to the existing line of code.

Some facets are empty as there are no rows in the data with those facet values, like males with 6 parents / children onboard.
From the graph, we can see that most of the passengers on the Titanic were males with no parents or children onboard, and of these males most of them were in the 3rd ticket class.
We can also see that in general, the number of passengers gets less as we look at increasing numbers of parents or children on board.
